# Mobile Guide

This guide defines how agents and developers must implement mobile apps code Clean Architecture with feature-based modules.

## Goals

- Keep business rules independent from framework details.
- Scale by feature without creating cross-module coupling.
- Make route files thin and push logic into `src/`.
- Keep components reusable, testable, and easy to reason about.

## Folder Structure

```text
app/                       # Expo Router entrypoints only
  _layout.tsx
  (tabs)/
    _layout.tsx
    index.tsx
    explore.tsx
  modal.tsx
src/
  app/                     # App-level composition (providers, navigation)
    navigation/
    providers/
  pages/                   # Route-level page modules (UI composition only)
    home-page/
    explore-page/
    modal-page/
  features/                # User-value interactions (per feature)
    home-feed/
      data/
      lib/
      model/
      ui/
    explore-categories/
      data/
      lib/
      model/
      ui/
  entities/                # Domain entities and shared domain types
    book/
      model/
  shared/                  # Cross-feature technical building blocks
    config/
    lib/
    ui/
```

## Layer Responsibilities

- `app`: global providers, navigation setup, app bootstrap wiring.
- `pages`: assemble screen-level UI using features and shared primitives.
- `features`: use-cases and feature-specific logic.
- `entities`: domain types and business model definitions.
- `shared`: generic UI components, hooks, and configs without domain meaning.

## Dependency Rules

Allowed import direction only:

`app -> pages -> features -> entities -> shared`

Additional rules:

- `shared` cannot import from any higher layer.
- `entities` can import only from `shared`.
- `features` can import from `entities` and `shared`.
- `pages` can import from `features`, `entities`, `shared`.
- `app` can import from all lower layers.
- Files inside `app/` (Expo Router) must import page/app modules only, not business logic.

## Segment Intent Inside Each Feature

- `model/`: interfaces, contracts, types, repository ports.
- `data/`: repository implementations, adapters, external source integration.
- `lib/`: use-cases and pure business orchestration.
- `ui/`: hooks and presentational feature components.
- `index.ts`: public API for external imports.

## Coding Workflow For New Feature

1. Create `src/features/<feature-name>/`.
2. Define contracts in `model/` (types, repository interface).
3. Implement use-case in `lib/`.
4. Implement data source in `data/` (API/local/mock).
5. Expose a hook or component in `ui/`.
6. Export only intended public symbols in `index.ts`.
7. Consume from `src/pages/<page-name>/ui/<page>.tsx`.
8. Keep Expo Router file as a route adapter only.

## Route File Rule (Critical)

`app/` files are adapters, not feature logic containers.

Good:

```ts
import { HomePage } from '@/pages/home-page';
export default function Route() {
  return <HomePage />;
}
```

Bad:

- defining use-case logic directly inside `app/(tabs)/index.tsx`
- calling repositories directly from route files
- importing low-level data adapters in route files

## Public API Rule

Every slice should expose an `index.ts` file. External layers should import from these public entrypoints instead of deep internal paths.

## Quality Checklist Before Finishing

- Imports follow allowed direction.
- No business logic in route files.
- Feature use-cases are isolated in `lib/`.
- Data access goes through repository contracts from `model/`.
- UI layer only orchestrates hooks/use-cases and rendering.
- `npm run lint` passes for `apps/mobile`.
